Your documentation is outdated. You do not notice until a crisis. During the crisis, you need the documentation. It is wrong. The habit of weekly updates would have prevented this.

A weekly documentation update habit is a 30-minute session every week. The team reviews the documentation. Updates what is outdated. Adds what is missing. The documentation stays current.

Here is why the payoff is highest in crises.

During a crisis, the team needs accurate information. The runbook. The contact list. The configuration details. If the documentation is current, the team finds the answer in seconds. If it is outdated, the team wastes time searching.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we implemented a weekly documentation habit. The team spent 30 minutes every Friday updating documentation. During a crisis three months later, the team resolved the issue in 40 minutes. The documentation had the exact steps. Without the habit, the resolution would have been estimated at 4 hours.

The habit cost 30 minutes a week. The crisis savings was 3 hours. The ROI was 6x for a single crisis.

The teams that update documentation when they remember are the ones with outdated docs. The teams that update weekly are the ones with current docs.

Spend 30 minutes a week. The documentation stays current. The crises resolve faster.
